.Dd 2026-06-12
.Dt MLOCK 1
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm mlock
.Nd monkey-themed screen locker for X
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl v
.Op Fl t Ar title
.Op Fl s Ar subtitle
.Op Fl b Ar bottomtext
.Op Ar cmd Op Ar arg ...
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
locks every screen of the current X display and waits for the user's
password. While locked it shows a configurable emoji, a title, a subtitle
and a footer line, all centered per physical monitor. The background color,
the emoji and the texts change with the lock state: idle, typing (two
alternating colors), wrong password, and caps lock active.
.Pp
If
.Ar cmd
is given, it is executed after the screen has been locked.
.Sh OPTIONS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl v
Print version information to stdout and exit.
.It Fl t Ar title
Override the main centered text. An empty string disables it.
.It Fl s Ar subtitle
Override the subtitle shown below the title. An empty string disables it.
.It Fl b Ar bottomtext
Override the footer text. It is expanded with
.Xr strftime 3 ,
so it can act as a clock, e.g.
.Qq It is %H:%M .
An empty string disables it.
.El
.Sh SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS
.Nm
reads the password hash from
.Pa /etc/shadow
and therefore must be installed setuid root; it drops privileges to the
user and group configured in
.Pa config.h
(default: nobody/nobody) right after startup, before any font or text
rendering happens. The whole process is locked into RAM with
.Xr mlockall 2
so the typed password can never be written to swap.
.Pp
On Linux, the OOM killer is disabled for the
.Nm
process to prevent it from being killed while the screen is locked.
.Sh CUSTOMIZATION
.Nm
is customized by editing
.Pa config.h
(created from
.Pa config.def.h )
and (re)compiling the source code. This keeps it fast, secure and simple.
.Sh EXAMPLES
Lock the screen and suspend:
.Dl mlock systemctl suspend
.Pp
Lock with custom texts:
.Dl mlock -t \(dqgone for lunch\(dq -s \(dq\(dq -b \(dqback at %H:30\(dq
